Test Multivariate IRT Model

2022-02-08

FLPS model

  • FLPS models with one factor and two factor

generate data

  • makeDat() function generates a list of data, which contains the data (stan_dt) for stan() to run the FLPS model. The list of data contains all other simulation inputs as well.

code

# generate data ------------------------------------------
sim_condition <- list(
  N       = 2000,     # sample size
  R2Y     = 0.2,      # strength of effects of covariates
  R2eta   = 0.2,      # strength of effects of latent variable
  omega   = 0.2,      # a11
  tau0    = 0.4,      # b0
  tau1    = -0.2,     # b11
  linear  = T,
  lambda  = 0.6,      # percentage of missing in latent variable models
  nsec    = 20,       # Number of items
  nfac    = 1,        # Number of latent factors
  lvmodel ="2pl"      # Type of latent models: 2pl, gpcm, grm
)

sdat <- do.call("makeDat", sim_condition)

  • To make sure the item response data is based on the population parameters, I ran mirt() and extracted the item parameters using coef(). The estimates with the generated response data is on the left-hand side, and the population value is on the right-hand side.
# Generated item parameters
check_lv(
 dat=sdat$lv.resp,
 covdata=NULL,
 lvmodel=sdat$lvmodel,

check flps model part

  • To make sure the data is generated by the FLPS model parameters set by the condition, I ran a simple regression with interaction terms (because I have true eta scores) using lm().
check_flps(sdat$stan_dt) %>% round(3)
##    b00     b0    b11    a11    by1    by2   bu11   bu12 
##  0.001  0.402 -0.200  0.220  1.011  0.487 -0.990  0.470

Run stan()

  • Using sdat$stan_dt as an input data for stan(), the FLPS model can be conducted. According to the type of latent variable model, different stan scripts will be fed into file. In this example, the IRT model script is used. Other scripts are:

  • 2PL: multivariate IRT

  • GPCM: multivariate GPCM

  • GRM: multivariate GRM

fit <- rstan::stan(
  file = "inst/stan/psIRT_multi.stan",
  data = sdat$stan_dt,
  iter = 6000,
  warmup = 2000,
  chains = 1,
  open_progress = F
)

Results

  • I ran 3 IRT models (2PL, GPCM, and GRM) varying the number of latent factors (1 and 2).

  • With one factor, the estimates are close to the parameter values.

  • With two factors, b11 or b12 (interaction effects, tau1) are biased, which needs to be investigated.
